\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {0.1.2}{\ignorespaces Successive and non--orthogonality contributions to the amplitude describing two--nucleon transfer in second order DWBA, entering in the expression of the absolute differential cross section $d\sigma /d\Omega =\genfrac  {}{}{}1{\mu _i\mu _f}{(4\pi \hbar ^2)^2}\genfrac  {}{}{}1{k_f}{k_i}\left |T^{(1)}+T_{succ}^{(2)}-T^{(2)}_{NO}\right |$. Concerning $T^{(1)}$ we refer to Fig. 0.1.1\hbox {}. In the upper part of the figure the coordinates used to describe the intermediate channel $d+F(\equiv A+1)$ are given, while in the lower part the corresponding expressions are displayed \citep  {Potel:13b} in the case of a ($t,p$) process. Schematically, the three contributions $T^{(1)}, T^{(2)}_{succ}$ and $T^{(2)}_{NO}$ to the transfer amplitude can be written as $\delimiter "426830A pB|v|tA\delimiter "526930B $, $\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ \delimiter "426830A pB|v|dF\delimiter "526930B \delimiter "426830A dF|v|tA\delimiter "526930B $ and $\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ \delimiter "426830A pB|v|dF\delimiter "526930B \delimiter "426830A dF|\mathbb  I|tA\delimiter "526930B $ respectively, where $v$ is the proton--neutron interaction and $\mathbb  I$ the unit oprerator. Within this context, while $T^{(2)}_{NO}$ receives contributions from the intermediate (virtual) closed ($d+F$) channel as $T^{(2)}_{succ}$ does, it is first order in $v$ as $T^{(1)}$.}}{3}}
